13
00:00:51,600 --> 00:00:54,559
I'm Pat Walls, and this is Starter Story.

14
00:00:54,559 --> 00:00:56,320
All right, Dennis, welcome to the channel.

15
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:58,800
Tell me about who you are, what you built, and what's your story.

16
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:00,000
>> Hello, my name is Dennis.

17
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:01,039
I built Yaphone.

18
00:01:01,039 --> 00:01:02,960
It makes $14,000 a month.

19
00:01:02,960 --> 00:01:08,159
I launched it in March 2025, days after Microsoft announced that it was closing Skype.

20
00:01:08,159 --> 00:01:13,040
And in under 7 months, we've gone from zero customers to 10,000 registered users.

21
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:13,520
>> Okay.

22
00:01:13,520 --> 00:01:17,200
7 months to get to 14,000 MR is insane.

23
00:01:17,200 --> 00:01:20,080
Can you share some more of the numbers behind this very fast growth?

24
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:23,840
>> So, in the first month when we just launched, the other phone made $4,000.

25
00:01:23,840 --> 00:01:27,360
Two months three, we've climbed to $10,800.

26
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:33,600
And last month, so on the 6 months of the existence of Yodafone, it made $13,300.

27
00:01:33,600 --> 00:01:38,320
In these 7 months, in total, we reached more than 10,000 registered users.

28
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:41,600
4,500 became paying individual customers.

29
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:46,399
And as we also have a B2B segment, we have 20 enterprise clients.

30
00:01:46,399 --> 00:01:51,840
In September, Yadafhone users made in total 27,000 calls.

31
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:58,960
And this statistic means that at any given moment in September, somebody was using my website to make a call.

32
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:02,079
>> Okay, let's dive into this very fast growing app here.

33
00:02:02,079 --> 00:02:07,680
It sounds like it's something similar to Skype, but can you explain to me what Yataphone is and what type of customers use it?

34
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:11,840
>> Yafone lets people make and receive cheap international calls right in browser.

35
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:14,319
International calls are generally very very expensive.

36
00:02:14,319 --> 00:02:20,480
A 10-minute call uh could easily cost you between $50 and $100 depending on your country and provider.

37
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:24,319
Yaphone solves this problem by using the voiceover IP technology.

38
00:02:24,319 --> 00:02:28,800
That means that you can call any mobile or London number for cents.

39
00:02:28,800 --> 00:02:35,200
Our clients are travelers, expats or just in general businesses that need to make a lot of calls.

40
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:44,640
Yeton is a pay as you go international calling service and that really differs us from most of the other competitors out there because the others operate on a SAS model.

41
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:51,920
That means that if you are an individual customer, you need to uh buy subscription that usually costs uh $30 a month or more.

42
00:02:51,920 --> 00:02:57,920
And if you're a business, you need to buy a seat or a subscription for each of the members of your organization.

43
00:02:57,920 --> 00:03:06,159
We allow businesses to just purchase a certain number of credits and then all of the organization members of this business can just use this central balance to make holes.

44
00:03:06,159 --> 00:03:09,280
Whenever you run out of credits, you can just top them up and that's it.

45
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:09,519
Okay.

46
00:03:09,519 --> 00:03:14,159
Before we get into the idea and how you came up with it, I want to know a little bit more about your background.

47
00:03:14,159 --> 00:03:17,040
I understand you don't come from a crazy technical background.

48
00:03:17,040 --> 00:03:18,720
Can you tell me a little bit more about that?

49
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:21,040
Uh >> I have no technical background whatsoever.

50
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:23,120
I actually I'm a trained diplomat.

51
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:25,519
So I used to study for diplomatic work in Russia.

52
00:03:25,519 --> 00:03:26,720
Then I moved to Austria.

53
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:31,120
I quickly understood that I wanted to uh work in a startup as a programmer.

54
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:35,200
So I taught myself how to code in two months mainly with books and courses.

55
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:39,440
Then I actually started working at the company and I realized that this is not the thing for me.

56
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:42,799
I want to have my own startup instead of working at somebody else's company.

57
00:03:42,799 --> 00:03:45,280
I started to do freelancing to support myself.

58
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:48,239
At any given moment, I was working on something on the site.

59
00:03:48,239 --> 00:03:51,040
And my first projects, they were ugly.

60
00:03:51,040 --> 00:03:52,080
They had no users.

61
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:56,640
Then slowly with each of them, with each of my projects, I learned one thing or the other.

62
00:03:56,640 --> 00:03:58,159
My design started to be better.

63
00:03:58,159 --> 00:04:00,000
My code started to be more reliable.

64
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:07,680
With each of the projects, I just learned something new and eventually it all piled up into this set of skills that ultimately let me build the other phone.

65
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:17,440
I love that you built a lot of projects and you built up a lot of skills that eventually led you to the right timing to build something that took off which ended up being Yataphone.

66
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:21,040
Can you give me a little bit more details about how you found the idea for Yatafone?

67
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:26,160
I travel a lot when it comes to government offices, banks, businesses, migration authorities.

68
00:04:26,160 --> 00:04:27,520
They are not on messenger apps.

69
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:31,840
The only way to call them if you need something is physically making a call.

70
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:34,000
And doing it abroad is freaking expensive.

71
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,680
I've always been using Skype for that.

72
00:04:35,680 --> 00:04:37,120
I've been their loyal client.

73
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:41,919
And then in March 2025, Microsoft announced that they were closing it down.

74
00:04:41,919 --> 00:04:49,440
Then I saw a tweet by Peter Levelvels saying that he and his friends were also using Skype and he was quite pissed that Microsoft was closing it down.

75
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:52,240
He encouraged people publicly to build a Skype alternative.

76
00:04:52,240 --> 00:04:53,600
And I thought, why not me?

77
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:57,919
Turns out I'm not the only person using Skype to make international calls, which I didn't know.

78
00:04:57,919 --> 00:05:00,479
And then I just built a quick prototype over the weekend.

79
00:05:00,479 --> 00:05:08,000
I launched it on Reddit and X and got my first sales in minutes, which never happened to me before in any of my previous projects.

80
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:08,160
>> Okay.

81
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:09,600
I mean, that's amazing.

82
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:11,280
You saw an idea on Twitter.

83
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:16,400
You had built up all these skills from all these kind of previous projects and you decided to build it.

84
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:20,000
Can you go a little bit deeper on how you actually built this app?

85
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:24,720
>> When I first started building my site projects, I just used React, JavaScript, HTML,

86
00:05:24,720 --> 00:05:26,000
CSS, regular stuff.

87
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:29,840
Then Nex.js came out and it turns out that you can build stuff pretty quickly with it.

88
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:33,520
So I used Nex.js as a fullstrike framework for my application.

89
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:37,280
I used Corser and LMS but it doesn't always look great.

90
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:41,680
So I had to correct a lot of things and tweak stuff on the design site manually.

91
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:41,919
Okay.

92
00:05:41,919 --> 00:05:46,639
What I love about this story Dennis is that you built this tool in just one weekend.

93
00:05:46,639 --> 00:05:49,520
You didn't spend months planning or overthinking the idea.

94
00:05:49,520 --> 00:05:51,199
You had already built the skills.

95
00:05:51,199 --> 00:05:52,880
Now was time to just execute.

96
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:55,360
You built a simple landing page and you just launched it.

97
00:05:55,360 --> 00:06:02,080
And this is proof that when you actually learn to build and ship, your life can change in just one weekend.

98
00:06:02,080 --> 00:06:05,759
And this is exactly what we do inside Starter Story Build.

99
00:06:05,759 --> 00:06:11,919
It's our program where you will learn how to build and launch your project using AI coding tools in just a couple weeks.

100
