The best part is that you don't even need to know how to code.

101
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:19,759
You can just show up, follow our building framework, and finally ship that idea to the world.

102
00:06:19,759 --> 00:06:22,880
Our next AI build boot camp is starting this week.

103
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:28,080
So, if you are ready to build, head to the first link in the description to claim your spot.

104
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:29,680
All right, let's get back to the interview.

105
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:33,440
Okay, so you mentioned that you launched this and you got users overnight.

106
00:06:33,440 --> 00:06:35,919
That's obviously not the case for a lot of people watching this.

107
00:06:35,919 --> 00:06:38,319
They've probably built stuff and that didn't happen.

108
00:06:38,319 --> 00:06:42,880
So, tell me the exact things you did that made this app successful so quickly.

109
00:06:42,880 --> 00:06:45,840
Back then, I didn't have any social media audience whatsoever.

110
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:49,600
I used to have 60 followers on Twitter for years, but I knew how Reddit works.

111
00:06:49,600 --> 00:06:54,800
And the thing about Reddit is that you can get millions of impressions without having any followers at all.

112
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:59,520
I launched products on it before I got blocked a lot, but I knew how to write stuff up,

113
00:06:59,520 --> 00:07:02,080
which subs to target, which tone of voice to use.

114
00:07:02,080 --> 00:07:04,240
So, I decided to launch primarily on Reddit.

115
00:07:04,240 --> 00:07:08,800
My first post was just screenshots of the core functionality of my app, which I think really made it stand out.

116
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:14,000
It was a very simple and clean web dialer interface and a couple of sentences about the product.

117
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:18,800
I wrote to the subreddits for travelers because I thought that this is my main core audience.

118
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:22,080
I got blocked there really fast and it was quite demotivating.

119
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:26,240
But before I got blocked, I had enough time for the users to see my post.

120
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:31,440
The most crazy thing is that I got the first sales minutes after my first Reddit post.

121
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:36,160
I've never seen anything like that before and that was a clear sign that my idea was validated.

122
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:39,280
Then I started posting regularly on subreddits for entrepreneurs.

123
00:07:39,280 --> 00:07:44,400
A very good thing about entrepreneur subreddits is that there you can first of all showcase your project,

124
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:49,120
promote your project yourself and you can also post links to your projects and you don't get blocked for this.

125
00:07:49,120 --> 00:07:51,680
In the first week, I got 150 users.

126
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:52,800
>> Okay, so that's amazing.

127
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:56,080
You post on Reddit, it got blocked, but you still got paying users.

128
00:07:56,080 --> 00:07:58,800
I'm curious, you had a bunch of apps that you built before.

129
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:01,919
They clearly didn't have this sort of validation or traction.

130
00:08:01,919 --> 00:08:05,520
What do you think you did right or got right with Yataphone?

131
00:08:05,520 --> 00:08:09,039
I think the key thing about this idea is that it's not an idea at all.

132
00:08:09,039 --> 00:08:20,400
It's a validated market which was first validated with the tweet by Peter levels I saw and then by sales I got from my Reddit post and apart from that it was a combination of a very good timing because at the time Microsoft

133
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:22,240
announced it was closing Skype down.

134
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:30,080
People started looking for alternatives and that created a lot of virality around all posts that were connected with this kind of big news event.

135
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:36,159
And the third component is that I just had enough skills at that point that I could create something that looked good,

136
00:08:36,159 --> 00:08:39,360
solved a real problem, and people were willing to pay for it.

137
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:40,880
Okay, so that's amazing.

138
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:45,440
Proven market, a little bit of timing, and you had set yourself up for success.

139
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:47,040
I think that's a great recipe.

140
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:48,800
That brings me to my next question.

141
00:08:48,800 --> 00:08:56,240
For anybody watching this, if you were to start over again, what would be your playbook to build a successful app like Yataphone right now?

142
00:08:56,240 --> 00:09:00,640
I would say that the first step is find a market where your competitors are dinosaurs.

143
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:02,560
They are old-fashioned and slowmoving.

144
00:09:02,560 --> 00:09:07,040
Yaf phone is not the only app on the market that's offering international calling.

145
00:09:07,040 --> 00:09:11,680
I have competitors and they've been on this market for 20 some cases or 30 years.

146
00:09:11,680 --> 00:09:18,720
But the thing is that those kind of companies are very slow to change and to adapt to changing market conditions.

147
00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:23,440
Those markets have validated demand and you can get usability and design really fast,

148
00:09:23,440 --> 00:09:25,680
better than those old-fashioned competitors.

149
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:30,880
Step two, build your MVP really fast and start posting about it everywhere on X, Reddit,

150
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:32,880
LinkedIn, whatever social media you can find.

151
00:09:32,880 --> 00:09:34,640
Your MVP doesn't have to be perfect.

152
00:09:34,640 --> 00:09:37,040
Try to nail design and usability.

153
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,680
Make sure that your core feature works well.

154
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:44,000
In the case of Yodafone, that was plainly making an outbound call from the app.

155
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,640
And make sure you have a compelling story to tell.

156
00:09:46,640 --> 00:09:53,279
This is especially important for Reddit because people there are really fast to scroll and they will disregard stuff that's not interesting for them.

157
00:09:53,279 --> 00:09:58,000
My story was of a lone engineer that was standing up to take the place of a giant company.

158
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:02,160
Step three, when a big competitor leaves, they have a lot of articles still mentioning them.

159
00:10:02,160 --> 00:10:10,000
And that's a great chance to rank on keywords that would you would otherwise never have a chance to rank for without a high domain authority website.

160
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:16,720
People think you need to be a big established company to get mentioned in high authority blog posts and articles,

161
00:10:16,720 --> 00:10:17,839
but this is just not true.

162
00:10:17,839 --> 00:10:20,079
My process was like this, and it's really simple.

163
00:10:20,079 --> 00:10:24,160
I looked for the keywords that I wanted to rank on, like for example, Skype alternative.

164
00:10:24,160 --> 00:10:29,680
Then I found the blog posts that were ranking there and tried to find the authors of those blog posts.

165
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:36,480
Sometimes it was X, sometimes LinkedIn, sometimes email, but I just wrote directly to the offers asking whether they could mention Yaphone.

166
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:41,360
They either agreed to add my tool, their blog post, or just replace Skype with Yaphone altogether.

167
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:48,640
And this felt crazy because Yafon replaced a giant wellestablished brand name and that obviously draw a lot of traffic to my website.

168
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:50,560
Step four, keep iterating.

169
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:54,959
I used to text every single paying customer for 6 months asking for feedback.

170
00:10:54,959 --> 00:10:57,440
I just add, "Hey, I'm Dennis, the founder of Yadafone.

171
00:10:57,440 --> 00:11:01,440
I would be thrilled to know what you think about the app and how your experience was so far."

172
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:04,800
This is timeconuming and you don't always have the energy as a founder for it.

173
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:10,240
But this is immensely helpful because it helps you figure out what are user segments and who your app is serving the best.

174
00:11:10,240 --> 00:11:18,560
and also it's catching the bad reviews early and you have the chance to react to bad experiences with your app before people go and give you bad reviews.

175
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:21,519
Step five, create a B2B app as soon as possible.

176
00:11:21,519 --> 00:11:24,160
Enterprise has bigger checks and much lower churn.

177
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:29,680
When I started with Yathon, I thought it would be a pure B2C app for travelers and expats to call abroad.

178
00:11:29,680 --> 00:11:32,079
I created my enterprise plan totally by accident.

179
00:11:32,079 --> 00:11:37,680
A guy texted me in the middle of the night asking if Yafon has a enterprise plan for his organization.

180
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:38,880
I said, "Of course we do."

181
00:11:38,880 --> 00:11:40,320
And to tell you secret, we didn't.

182
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:46,320
I coded my enterprise plan in a panic mode through the night because the next morning I had to live life demo it in front of this customer.

183
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:50,959
By the way, he is still a Yan customer paying around $1,000 for it each month.

184
00:11:50,959 --> 00:11:53,680
So yeah, that would be my playbook if I was starting today.

185
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:54,480
Thanks for sharing that.

186
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:55,600
I think that was awesome.

187
00:11:55,600 --> 00:11:59,680
I'm going to switch topics a little bit and I want to learn about how you built this.

188
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:00,800
What's your tech stack?

189
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:03,200
What kind of tech are you using to build this software?

190
00:12:03,200 --> 00:12:06,480
>> I use cursor for coding and also sometimes writing copy.

191
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,800
Versell for hosting uh my solution.

192
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:12,720
I duke my keyword research with hrefs and I use stripe for payments.

193
00:12:12,720 --> 00:12:16,000
Also with AI it's very easy to build your own custom solutions.

194
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:19,600
I built my own system for handling support requests and admin panel with cursor.

195
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:24,000
I catch most support requests early so that I can regulate my workflow.

196
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,600
I can be very efficient with support and can afford to stay solo founder thanks to it.

197
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:33,760
My main cost is Twilio that is handling calls and I pay them around 35% of my monthly earnings.

198
00:12:33,760 --> 00:12:36,560
Okay, thanks for sharing that, being transparent about the numbers.

199
00:12:36,560 --> 00:12:43,440
The last question that I have for you that we ask all founders who come on starter story for anyone who's watching this that wants to start something like you,

200
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:47,839
a BTOC app, a SAS, anything online, what would be your advice?

201
00:12:47,839 --> 00:12:52,800
>> I would advise to do search engine optimization from day one and you have to be very patient with it.

202
00:12:52,800 --> 00:12:56,800
I think SEO is pure magic to most developers because it doesn't come naturally to us.

203
00:12:56,800 --> 00:12:58,560
We are used to quick feedback loops.

204
00:12:58,560 --> 00:13:04,240
You change something in your code editor, seconds after you see the changes taking effect uh in your local host.

205
00:13:04,240 --> 00:13:05,680
With SEO, it's not the case.

206
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:10,240
SEO changes take weeks, sometimes even months, but it pays off immensely.

207
00:13:10,240 --> 00:13:14,000
My competitors started ranking better for the keywords I targeted.

208
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:18,720
Even though I was first to the market, I looked at the SEO, chatted a lot with Chad GPT about it,

209
00:13:18,720 --> 00:13:21,839
and then it turns out it was a very small stupid detail.

210
00:13:21,839 --> 00:13:26,880
My site map didn't have a 3W prefix, and Google just ignored all the pages I wanted to rank.

211
00:13:26,880 --> 00:13:29,600
So, you have to be very attentive to details with this show.

212
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:31,040
>> Okay, thanks for coming on, Dennis.

213
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:35,279
I'm going to be checking my site map right after this and make sure I got that www in there.

214
00:13:35,279 --> 00:13:36,880
But, dude, you built an awesome business.

